@course

id: book:emotional-design-rwmt
title: Emotional Design
author: Donald A. Norman
description: How three layers of feeling decide which objects we love and which we forget.
color: C85159
genres: design, psychology, user-experience
relevant_for: designers, product-managers, anyone

@segment
Three Layers of Feeling
TLF

@package
Before the Mind Catches Up
Free
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @pause, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant E (2 stories), default intro, teaching: the visceral level

@text
Some objects in a shop catch the eye before the price tag has been read.
The hand reaches for the scissors, the coffee cup, or the wooden spoon.
The choice happens before any thought arrives.
So what is making the decision in that half-second?

@text
Newborns just hours old will turn their heads toward a face shape drawn on a card.
The face does not need to be a real person.
Two black dots and a curve are enough.
The same babies ignore a card with the same dots arranged in any other pattern.
Nobody taught them what a face is.
The eyes were already looking for one before the babies had ever seen a face.

@text
Researchers find the same kind of pull in adults, just hidden under decades of habit.
A symmetrical face is rated more attractive than an asymmetrical one without the rater knowing why.
A round, smooth shape draws the hand before an angular one does.
A polished surface holds the eye longer than a rough one.
None of these preferences need to be learned.
They were already wired into the body before any culture could teach them otherwise.

@question
What is the experiment with the newborns showing?

answer: Babies need to see real faces to learn what a face looks like.
consequence: The babies had never seen a face before the test, but they still preferred the face shape.

answer: The brain is born already looking for face shapes, before any learning happens.
consequence: The wiring for face shapes is built into the body before any face has been seen.

answer: The shapes had nothing to do with face recognition; the babies were just curious.
consequence: The babies turned only toward the face shape and ignored the other patterns made of the same dots.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The brain is born with a small bias toward certain shapes, faces among the strongest of them.
hint: Notice that the babies had never seen a real face before the test.

@pause
Long before there were knives or coffee cups, the eye had already decided which berries to pick first.

@text
<c:g>The visceral level</c:g> is the first layer of how design reaches inside the person.
It is the wiring that turned the newborn's head toward the face card, before the baby had ever seen a face.
The same wiring makes the adult hand reach for the smooth handle instead of the angular one.
It decides in the half-second between seeing and knowing, before any thought arrives.
The wiring sits below culture and below language.
A child in a market and an engineer in a lab obey the same instincts.

@true_false
Aesthetic taste is mostly learned from culture, with very little built into the body at birth.

true: True, taste is almost entirely cultural.
consequence: The visceral layer underneath the cultural one is built in and runs the same in any country.

false: False, the visceral layer is hardwired before any culture arrives.
consequence: A newborn turns toward a face card the same way in every country.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The visceral level is hardwired. The layers above it are shaped by where someone grew up, but the foundation is shared.
hint: A baby in any country reaches for the same shapes before learning a single word.

@text
The visceral layer is the half-second jolt, the body recognising shapes before the mind catches up.
That layer is only the start.
A second layer wakes up later, when the eye gives way to the hand.

@package
What the Hand Learns Next
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant B (2 stories), misconception intro, teaching: the behavioral level

@text
Most people assume the favourite kitchen tool is <c:r>the one that looked best in the shop</c:r>.
Pretty knives, shiny pans, and famous-brand mugs all win the day they arrive home.
They sit on the counter like trophies, ready to be used.

@text
A woman receives two knives as a gift on the same day.
The first is a sleek German blade, expensive, with a polished black handle.
The second is a battered wooden-handled knife from her grandmother's kitchen, slightly chipped along the edge.
The German knife is the one she shows off when guests visit.
The grandmother's knife is the one she reaches for every time she actually cooks.
After six months, the German knife still feels like a display.

@text
Years pass.
The woman has cooked thousands of meals with the grandmother's knife.
Her hand reaches for it without looking, the way the hand reaches for a familiar pen.
The German knife sits clean in the drawer, almost as new as the day it arrived.
When she uses other knives in friends' kitchens, every one feels strange and unbalanced.
What she loves about the old knife is how it answers her grip.

@question
What is making the woman keep choosing the grandmother's knife?

answer: The German knife is poorly designed and uncomfortable.
consequence: The German knife is well made. The story is about a different kind of fit.

answer: The grandmother's knife rewards the hand each time it is picked up.
consequence: The grandmother's knife sits in the hand like a familiar pen, and the hand keeps returning for that reward.

answer: Sentimental value, because the knife belonged to her grandmother.
consequence: Sentiment matters in another layer of the brain. This story is about the hand and the body.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A tool that fits the hand becomes a small reward every time it is picked up. The body files those rewards away over time.
hint: Notice what the hand is feeling, not what the eye is seeing.

@text
<c:g>The behavioral level</c:g> plays out after the half-second of looking is over.
It is the second layer of how design reaches inside the person, running during the long minutes of actually using something.
It is what the grandmother's knife is using to win, every time the hand reaches into the drawer.
Every time the hand picks the knife up, the fit and the balance reward the body without the mind noticing.
The favourite tool, in any drawer, is the one that has rewarded the hand the most.

@true_false
A well-designed tool is one that always wins the buying decision in the shop.

true: True, the best tools win on first sight.
consequence: Looks decide what is bought. Use decides what becomes the favourite.

false: False, what makes a favourite tool happens after the tool reaches home.
consequence: The favourite is built over months of use, not chosen in the shop window.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The visceral level shapes what gets bought, and the behavioral level shapes what stays in the hand.
hint: Think about which tool in any kitchen actually gets used most often.

@reflect
A tool that looked right in the shop and felt wrong in the hand: a chef's knife or a fancy peeler.
A favourite kitchen item kept for how it sits in the hand: an old wooden spoon.
A small daily friction a better-shaped object would erase: a stiff handle or a sharp edge.

@text
The hand is the slow judge.
It learns the tool over months of use, and rewards the tool that fits.
But there is a third layer of how design touches feeling, and it lives somewhere even quieter than the hand.

@package
More Than the Object Itself
# @true_false, @text, @text, @question, @text, @reflect, @text
# Variant D (2 stories), true/false intro, teaching: the reflective level

@true_false
A pair of running shoes that no longer fits will usually be thrown away within the year.

true: True, broken shoes get replaced quickly.
consequence: That is what logic says. Look at any closet and the answer is often different.

false: False, some pairs sit in the closet for years after they fall apart.
consequence: The shoes that meant something tend to outlive the shoes that just worked.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A shoe that was part of an important moment can stay in the closet for years after it stops fitting. The body alone cannot hold the memory, so the object holds it instead.
hint: Look at any closet and count the items that still fit but are never worn.

@text
A man owns two watches.
Both keep time perfectly, both cost about the same, and both look fine on the wrist.
He almost always wears the second one.
The first watch was bought from a shop window.
The second was a gift from his father, given the month before his father died.
Asked which watch is better, he would say neither.
Asked which one he would feel terrible about losing, he would name the second without thinking.

@text
A young woman keeps a single mug at the back of her cupboard.
The handle is chipped, the glaze is fading, and the inside is stained from years of tea.
She has six newer mugs that look better and pour cleaner.
She bought the chipped mug for herself the week she moved into her own flat.
On the days when life is going badly, she takes the mug down and drinks tea from it.
Holding the mug for a few minutes makes the day feel slightly less heavy.

@question
What do the second watch and the chipped mug have in common?

answer: They are objectively better than the alternatives.
consequence: Both pairs of objects are equal in function. The second one wins on something else.

answer: They each carry a moment from the owner's life, and that moment is part of the object now.
consequence: An object can carry a piece of someone's history, and that piece becomes part of using the object.

answer: They were both more expensive than the alternatives.
consequence: Price has nothing to do with either story. The chipped mug was the cheapest in the cupboard.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Some objects become small monuments to a person or a moment. The owners keep using them long after better versions exist.
hint: Compare the function of each object with what each one means to the person holding it.

@text
A second-hand watch becomes a small monument to a father, and the time it keeps quietly turns secondary.
A chipped mug becomes the marker of a first home, and the tea it pours hardly matters anymore.
<c:g>The reflective level</c:g> sits above both the visceral and the behavioral, in the part of the mind that tells stories about the objects we keep.
It is what makes the watch and the mug refuse to leave, long after their use is gone.
The strongest objects in any home live on all three layers at once.

@reflect
An object kept at home for no practical reason: a postcard or a small stone.
A daily-use object that quietly holds a memory: a pen, a watch, or a ring.
A replacement that turned out quietly worse than the original: a chair or a knife.

@text
The thread of this course is that an object is never just an object to the person who owns it.
What gets called emotional design is the moment when all three layers line up inside the same object.
Maybe the harder question is which object in any room is quietly doing that right now.